[Line 138] ''

[Line 139] '### Example for the Bin Packing Problem:'

[Line 140] '- Each bin has a certain capacity, and each item has a size. The goal is to pack items into bins without exceeding the capacity.'

[Line 141] '- The priority function is used to determine which bin to place the item in first.'

[Line 142] ''

[Line 143] '### Additional Notes:'

[Line 144] '- The function needs to return an array where each element represents the priority of each bin for the given item.'

[Line 145] '- The priority can be any heuristic, but it must be based on the item size and the current state of the bins.'

[Line 146] ''

[Line 147] '### Hints:'

[Line 148] '- Common heuristics for bin packing include:'

[Line 149] '    - First Fit'

[Line 150] '    - Best Fit'

[Line 151] '    - First Fit Decreasing'

[Line 152] '    - Best Fit Decreasing'

[Line 153] '    - Worst Fit'

[Line 154] '    - Random'

[Line 155] '    - etc.'

[Line 156] ''

[Line 157] 'But these are algorithms for the entire packing process, not for the priority function.'

[Line 158] ''

[Line 159] "The priority function is a scoring function that determines the priority of each bin for the item. So, it's the scoring heuristic used within these algorithms."

[Line 160] ''

[Line 161] 'For example:'

[Line 162] '- First Fit uses the first bin that can fit the item, with priority being 1 if the bin can fit, else 0.'

[Line 163] '- Best Fit uses the bin that has the smallest space after placing the item.'

[Line 164] '- Worst Fit uses the bin that has the largest space after placing the item.'

[Line 165] ''

[Line 166] 'So, the priority function is the scoring function that, for each bin, gives a score based on how well the item fits into the bin.'

[Line 167] ''

[Line 168] 'So, for each bin, the priority function returns a score, and the bin with the highest score is selected.'

[Line 169] ''

[Line 170] "So, the priority function must compute, for each bin, a priority score based on the item and the bin's current state."

[Line 171] ''

